snippet.textDisplay:
Can we all just completely forget about the Lady Ghostbusters film? We should all just pretend that it didn't happened and never bring it up again. I'm being serious about this. We can just chalk it up as social amnesia.

Let's face it, it shouldn't exist in the first place. I think what really pisses me off is that the cast of Lady GBs is upset that the new film doesn't pay any homage to them. Which is hypocritical because their movie completely left out the original franchise.

This is what I can't stand about modern feminism. They want to make their mark in films and entertainment but they're just copying someone else's ideas. Is that how these "freethinking" ladies want to be remembered? By ripping off a man's intellectual property and making it their own? They did the same thing with the "Ocean's (11, 12, 13)" franchise.

Ladies, feminists, etc, go make something yourselves. Start with a concept, and follow it through. Stop riding on the coattails of your male counterparts and do your own thing.

I'll get off my soap box now, I'm just saying this new film is "Ghostbusters 3." We should get excited about it. I've been waiting for a third film for 30 years. I'm happy that it is happening. I just hope it turns out great.

snippet.textDisplay: I agree if GB 2016 never happened and 30 years later we had this teaser trailer I'd probably be overwhelmed with interest.  I'm the nostalgia king, I like old movies left alone... that's right Lucas don't try to fix the past.  New adaptations of classical films often tarnish the original and don't add newness to the story.  I'm ok with 3 Star Wars movies.  I'm ok with 2 Ghostbusters movies.  I still watch them.  I'm not ok with milking the masses with chum from grinding up these classics to make a buck or push some lame agenda.  If I cleanse my pallet from the aweful taste 2016 gave me, and yes i watched it open-minded with my Daughter and both of us left feeling like we watched a big turd not a movie.  This might be ok, it's at least intriguing and I like how it's picking up the past but will it be good?  Almost any movie will be better than GB 2016 so it certainly seems like it will at least accomplish that goal.  I like that it's the grandkids finding the stash of ghostbuster relics from a gone-bye era so I'm going to give it a chance like I gave 2016 a chance.  Unlike the Rise of Skywalker which put horses on a Star Destroyer instantly indicating to me, Disney won't ever get Star Wars so I'll pass.  Rant over.
